ownedComment.body: Author:s.dana. Created:1/10/14 10:02 AM. Title:. Comment:.
The root class/element; attributes pertain to the status and format of the report and when generated.
Identifies the time that the election report was generated.
Notes that can be added as appropriate, presumably by an adjudicator.
The type of report, using the ReportType enumeration.
If ReportType is 'other', this contains the report type.
The version of the CVR specification being used (1.0).
Identification of the device that has generated this CVR report.
Placeholder for an optional digital signature, using the W3C digital signature standard.

Represents a CVR generated by a scanner or other vote capture device, containing indications of the contests and ballot selections selected because of the voter’s ballot choices, as well as other information for auditing and annotation. Each sheet of a multi-page paper ballot is represented by an individual CVR, e.g., if all sheets of a 5-sheet ballot are scanned, 5 CVRs will be generated.
An identifier for the ballot that this CVR represents. If provided, this number must be the same on all CVRs that represent individual sheets from the same multi-sheet ballot.
An ordered list of pointers to image files of the scanner ballots.
The status of the CVR, e.g., adjudicated, counted, etc.
When BallotStatus is 'other', contains the ballot status.
An identifier of the ballot style of the ballot associated with this CVR.
The identifier for the batch that includes this CVR.
The sequence number of the corresponding paper ballot within a batch.
An optional, unique identifier for this CVR, used to link the CVR with the corresponding paper ballot, e.g., would contain the same value that the scanner stamped on the paper ballot when scanned.
The total number of write-ins in all contests of the CVR.
The sequence number for this CVR. This represents the ordinal number that this CVR was processed in by the tabulating device.
The device that generated the cast vote records.
Indicates the sheet number of the multi-sheet ballot being represented.
The smallest piece of geography associated with a voter's ballot or cast vote record at the smallest or lowest level (typically a precinct or split-precinct).
Used for identifying the geographical location, i.e., the reporting unit for the report generation device, which could be the precinct location of a scanner that generates a collection of CVRs.
A code associated with the reporting unit.
Name of the reporting unit.
Type of reporting unit, e.g., precinct, split-precinct, vote center, etc.
If Type is 'other', contains the reporting unit type.
The collection of cast vote records associated with the reporting unit and the reporting device.
Abstract class for a contest on the ballot that corresponds to this CVR. Classes for specific types of contests inherit the attributes and define their own.
An abbreviation associated with the contest.
A code or identified used for this contest.
Title or name of the contest, e.g., "Governor" or "Question on Legalization of Gambling".
The vote variation for this contest.
If VoteVariation is 'other', the vote variation for this contest.
Identifies a candidate in a contest on the ballot corresponding to the CVR.
The party associated with the candidate.
A code or identifier associated with the candidate.
Candidate's name as listed on the ballot.
Class for describing information about a political party associated with the CVR.
Short name for the party, e.g., "DEM".
Official full name of the party, e.g., "Republican".
Indentifies the type of contest as involving a ballot measures. Inherits attributes from the Contest class.
Identifies the type of contest as involving one or more candidates. Inherits attributes from the Contest class.
The party associated with the contest, if a partisan primary.
The number of candidates to be elected in the contest.
The number of votes allowed in the contest, e.g., 3 for a 'choose 3 of 5 candidates' contest.

Abstract class for a ballot selection in a contest on the ballot corresponding to this CVR or a CVR in the collection of CVRs. Classes for specific types of ballot selections inherit the attributes and define their own.
Class for a type of ballot selection specific to ballot measures, e.g., "yes", "no".
The selection, i.e., 'yes', 'no'.
Used for identifying the device that has generated the CVRs. CastVoteRecordReport refers to this class as ReportGeneratingDevice.
The application associated with the reporting device.
Manufacturer of the reporting device.
Manufacturer's model of the reporting device.
Additional explanatory notes as applicable.
Serial number or other identification that can uniquely identify the reporting device.
Class for a type of ballot selection specific to selecting a candidate in a contest for an office.
The candidate associated with this ballot selection.
A flag to indicate if the candidate selection is associated with a write-in.
Identifies the type of contest as involving a straight party selection. Inherits attributes from the Contest class.
Used in Code.Type to indicate the type of code/identifier being used.
Used to indicate that the identifier is a FIPS code.
Used to indicate that the identifier is from a local-level scheme, i.e., unique to a county or city.
Used to indicate that the identifier is from a national-level scheme other than FIPS or OCD-ID.
Used to indicate that the identifier is from the OCD-ID scheme.
Used to indicate that the identifier is from a state-level scheme, i.e., unique to a particular state.
Used when no other value in this enumeration applies to the identifier type.
Identifies the type of contest as involving a retention, such as for a judicial retention. Similar to a ballot measure contest and inherits attributes from Contest.
Serves to organize the CVRs per an election, e.g., for a device, a precinct, etc., and defines the contests, ballot selections, and candidates referenced in the CVRs.
Used for establishing a collection of contests that will be referenced by the CVRs.
Used to establish a collection of candidates, used for linking candidates to contests.
Used for a code associated with the election, e.g., a precinct identifier if the election scope is a precinct.
A text string identifying the election.
Identifies the election scope, i.e., the political geography corresponding to the election.
For a ballot selection specific to a party selection, i.e., for a ballot selection in a straight-party contest.
The party associated with the ballot selection.
Used in Election, GpUnit, Contest, Candidate, Party, to identify an associated code and the type of code.
A label associated with the code, used as needed.
The value of the code, i.e., the identifier.
Used to indicate the type of code, from the IdentifierType enumeration.
If Type is 'other', the type of code.
Used in GpUnit.Type to indicate the type of political geography, e.g., precinct, where the reporting device was located.
Used to indicate a combined precinct.
Used to indicate a polling place.
Used to indicate a precinct.
Used to indicate a split-precinct.
Used to indicate a vote-center.

Identifies a contest in which a ballot selection was made and associates the ballot selection(s). Overvotes plus Undervotes plus TotalVotes must equal the number of votes allowable in the contest, e.g., in a "chose 3 of 5" contest in which the voter chooses only 2, then Overvotes = 0, Undervotes = 1, and TotalVotes = 2, which adds up to the number of votes allowable = 3.
Used for an annotation that applies to the contest.
The number of votes lost due to overvoting.
??? Ask Sam.
The status of the contest, e.g., overvoted, undervoted, from the ContestStatus enumeration.
If Status is 'other', the status of the contest
The number of votes lost due to undervoting.
Used in CastVoteRecord.Status to identify the status of the ballot.
To indicate that the ballot has been adjudicated.
To indicate that the ballot has been counted.
To indicate that the ballot is invalid (not a ballot).
To indicate that the ballot needs to be adjudicated.
To indicate that the ballot was not entirely readable by the scanner.
Used when no other value in this enumeration applies to the ballot.

Used to indicate a ballot selection or marginal mark. The ballot selection could have been: a) marked by the voter, including for a write-in, or b) marked (generated) by the scanner per contest rules, or c) marked through adjudication, or d) determined by the scanner as being a marginal mark.

This will most typically have a multiplicity of 1, but can be multiple for contests that allow selecting multiple choices.
The order of this association can be used to determine candidate preference for appropriate voting variations.
Used to record an annotation made by one or more individuals, e.g., adjudicating aspects of the ballot.
The ordinal position of the selection as is appreared on the ballot.
The status of the ballot selection, e.g., 'marked-voter' for marked by the voter, taken from the BallotSelectionStatus enumeration.
If Status is 'other', contains the ballot status.
Contains further information about the mark made (e.g., by the voter) for the ballot selection.
For cumulative or range voting variations, this attribute represents the total number of votes indicated across all marks.
Used in ContestVote.Status to identify the status of a contest in which ballot selection(s) were made.
The contest has been adjudicated.
Used to indicate that the contest has been invalidated by the generating device because of contest rules.
Used to indicate that the contest was overvoted.
Used to indicate that the contest was undervoted.
Used when no other value in this enumeration applies to the contest.
Used in ContestVote.Status to identify the status of a ballot selection.
To indicate that the ballot selection was adjudicated.
To indicate that the ballot selection was generated per contest rules.
To indicate that the ballot selection was invalidated by the generating device because of contest rules.
To indicate that the ballot selection was flagged by the generating device for adjudication.
To indicate that the ballot selection was overvoted.
To indicate that the ballot selection was undervoted.
Used when no other value in this enumeration applies to the ballot selection.
Used to record annotations made by one or more adjudicators.
A message created by the annotator(s).
Name(s) of the adjudicator(s).
The date and time of an annotation.
The previous status (prior to the recording of the annotation) of the item being annotated, i.e., the CVR as a whole, a contest, a specific ballot selection, or a specific ballot mark.
Used in Contest.VoteVariation to indicate the vote variation (vote method) used to tabulate the contest.
Used in CastVoteRecordReport.ReportType to indicate the type of report.
Used when the report contains adjudications.
Used when the report is an aggregation of device reports.
Used when the report is an export from a device such as a scanner.
Used when the report is the result of a ranked choice voting round.
Used to hold the contents of a file, generally an image of a paper ballot or a write-in entered on to a paper ballot.
Contains the base64 binary contents of the file.
Contains the name of the file or an identifier of the file.
The mime type of the file, e.g., image/jpeg.
Used for a file containing an image, e.g., an image of a write-in on a paper ballot. .
Used when the ballot selection is for a write-in. WriteInBallotSelectionVote is a subclass of BallotSelectionVote and has additional attributes for the image and text of the write-in.
Used for the image of the write-in from paper ballot in base64 binary encoding and/or a file identifier for the file containing the image of the write-in.
Used for the text of the write-in. If the CVR is produced from a handwritten write-in on a paper ballot, the text would be added via adjudication.

Contains additional information about a (voter's) mark in a ballot selection. The number of potential VoteMarks that should be associated with a BallotSelection is (for paper ballots) the same as the number of ovals next to a particular choice. There will be usually 1 instance of VoteMark for plurality voting, but there could be multiple instances for RCV, approval, cumulative, or other vote variations in which a voter can select multiple candidates.
Used for an annotation that applies to the ballot selection.
For the RCV voting variation, the rank chosen by the voter.
The ordinal position of the mark within the ballot selection.
Status of the mark, e.g., marked-voter for marked by the voter, from the VoteMarkStatus enumeration.
If Status is 'other', the status of the ballot selection.
Used in VoteMark.Status to identify the status of a vote mark made for a ballot selection.
Used to indicate that the vote mark was adjudicated and is tabulatable.
Used to indicate that the vote mark was invalidated because of adjudication and is not tabulatable.
Used to indicate that the vote mark was generated by the generating device per contest rules and is tabulatable.
Used to indicate that the vote mark was invalidated by the generating device because of contest rules and is not tabulatable.
Used to indicate that the vote mark contains a marginal mark by the voter and is not tabulatable.
Used to indicate that the vote mark was made by the voter and is recognized as valid and is tabulatable.
Used when no other value in the enumeration applies to the vote mark.
Used for an image file, contains information about the file.
A pointer to the location of the image file.
Either a signature for the embedded image, or a detached signature for the image available at the specified location.
Contains a hash associated with the file.
The type of the hash, from the HashType enumeration.
If Type is 'other', the type of the hash.
The hash value, encoded as a string.
Used in Hash.type to indicate a type of hash used for an image file.

MarkMetric represents some generic measurement of a mark when the scanner can assign it, such as for mark density or quality. The type of the metric being used is determined by the 'Type' attribute of a MarkMetric instance.

The specific type of metric being used to determine quality. The supplied type must be specific enough that the attached value can be accurately verified later. For example, 'Acme Mark Density' may be a sufficiently specific type. However, if different machines determine the metric using a different algorithm, then it would be necessary to be more specific: 'Acme ImageCast Precinct Mark Density'
The string value of the metric specified by Type

A W3C standard data type for a binary floating-point number. The W3C definition of xsd:double is in http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/.
The xsd:double is a number where the value can be positive, negative, integer or floating point, with at least 7 digits of precision. Numbers are assumed to be positive but can be explicitly designated as positive by preceding the number with a ‘+’ (ASCII decimal 43) character. Negative numbers must be explicitly designated as negative by a preceding ‘–‘ (ASCII decimal 45) character. An internal representation of an IEEE double precision floating-point number is assumed. This range of values for IEEE doubles is defined as 3.4x10-38 ≤ value ≤ 3.4x10+38. The format for representing a double is the same as the format used in the computer languages C, Perl, Python, or TCL. For example, all the following are legal numbers:
1.005 ; 0.01; .01; -2.334e-33; .224e-2

A W3C standard data type for non-negative integer numbers. The W3C definition of xsd:nonNegativeInteger is in http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/.
The range of values allowed are 0 ≤ value ≤ 2147483647 (the non-negative values that fit in a 32 bit signed integer).

The W3C standard data type for the current date and time is xsd:dateTime. (See http://www.w3.org/TR/NOTE-datetime-970915.html.) The following formats from the W3C specification are recommended for 258X files:
Complete date plus hours, minutes and seconds:
YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ssTZD (e.g. 1997-07-16T19:20:30.4536+01:00)
Complete date plus hours, minutes, seconds and a decimal fraction of a Second:
YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss.sTZD (e.g. 1997-07-16T19:20:30.45+01:00)
where:
YYYY = four-digit year
MM = two-digit month (01=January, etc.)
DD = two-digit day of month (01 through 31)
Hh = two digits of hour (00 through 23) (am/pm NOT allowed)
Mm = two digits of minute (00 through 59)
Ss = two digits of second (00 through 59)
S = one or more digits representing a decimal fraction of a second
TZD = time zone designator (Z or +hh:mm or –hh:mm)
A W3C standard data type for a Unicode character string. The characters are from the UTF-8 character set as defined in http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2279.txt.
The data is encoded using base64. (see IETF RFC 1421 for the base64 algorithm and http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/#base64Binary)
A W3C standard data type for hyperlinks. The W3C definition of xsd:anyURI is in http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/.

A W3C standard data type for positive integer numbers. The W3C definition of xsd:positiveInteger is in http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/.
The range of values allowed are 1 ≤ value ≤ 2147483647 (the positive values that fit in a 32 bit signed integer).
The W3C standard for an unsigned byte (an unsigned 8 bit integer with a value between 0- 255.) The W3C definition of xsd:unsignedByte is in http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/.
